wrote:
&gt;&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;J. B. Rainsberger&quot; &lt;jbr@d...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; &gt; So said  Curt Sampson  on  2003-02-06 --------------------
&gt;&gt; &gt; 
&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;On Tue, 4 Feb 2003, Scott Stirling wrote:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;Yes, Kent Beck indeed did say, &quot;TDD followed religiously should 
&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt;result in 100% statement coverage.&quot;
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; That&#39;s pretty religious.  And not completely pragmatic.  Should you
&gt;&gt; test drive toSting() methods that you want for nice test failure
&gt;&gt; reports?  There are bits & piecs that very likely will slip through
&gt;&gt; untested.  Some aren&#39;t a problem. 
&gt;
&gt;I think I should say a bit more.  All business functionallity should
&gt;be 100% test covered.  Business functionallity should be fully test
&gt;driven.    So if you need a toString() for a business purpose, e.g.
&gt;for rendering something in a listbox, then it should be test driven. 
&gt;If it&#39;s just for inspecting or test message output, then I generally
&gt;wouldn&#39;t bother.
